  footnotes: []
english:
  title: 'Prayer for the Five Stars: A Ritual Text to Avert Celestial Calamities'
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven sends forth portents to awaken mankind—
    this is its way of teaching.
    How dare we presume to fathom the Buddha's dharma,
    which flows according to circumstance?

    When sincere devotion gathers, protection descends,
    and calamities dissolve before they take root.

    I humbly reflect: inheriting the blessings of ancestors,
    guarding the sacred authority of temple and shrine,
    I find no peace in my station, no lightness in my duties.
    Though I strive with diligence and care,
    my virtue falls short, my wisdom lacks luster—
    so there are surely omissions and losses.

    Is it not the discord of order and custom,
    the discord of cold and heat, rain and sun,
    that has grown so severe I find no moment's rest?
    Yet how much graver now—Jupiter strays from its course
    and dwells in the house of Mars!
    My dread deepens; my worry swells.

    I turn with urgent prayer to the supreme gate of Buddha's way,
    swiftly seeking shelter beneath his great compassion.
    Following the pure dharma, I arrange this sacred space,
    inviting the venerable monks in their humble robes,
    expounding the luminous sutras inscribed on palm leaves.

    Though my offerings are finer than a hair's breadth,
    may they echo like shadow and sound, touching the divine.

    I humbly pray:
    May calamities dissolve in silence,
    and blessings arrive in abundance.
    May warfare consume itself in flame,
    weapons be sheathed and laid to rest.
    May the nation's foundations grow ever stronger,
    enduring long and prospering forever.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The five stars (五星) refer to the classical five planets in Chinese astronomy: Jupiter, Mars, Saturn, Venus, and Mercury. Their irregular movements were interpreted as celestial omens.'
  - key: ''
    value: The 'supreme gate' (最勝之門) and 'great compassion' (大慈) are references to Buddhist concepts of enlightenment and divine mercy.
  - key: ''
    value: Palm leaves (貝文) refer to Buddhist scriptures, as Buddhist texts were traditionally written on palm leaves.
  - key: ''
    value: This text appears to be a formal petition or prayer ritual commissioned during a period when celestial irregularities were observed, likely interpreted as signs of political or natural disorder requiring spiritual intervention.
